 March 20.<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|2020-03-23\n|620\n|33\n|3\n|5\n|56\n|6\n|1\n|0\n|New cases characteristics: 3 males, 3 females; 23 healthcare workers, and two returnees from India and Bahrain. New death caused by community transmission.\n|-\n|2020-03-24\n|712\n|39\n|4\n|5\n|92\n|6\n|1\n|0\n|New positives include returnee from [[Saudi Arabia]] and 4 locals with epidemiological link. The death of the female was related to community transmission  \n|-\n|2020-03-25\n|794\n|39\n|5\n|5\n|82\n|0\n|1\n|6\n|\n|-\n|2020-03-26\n|920\n|44\n|5\n|11\n|126\n|5\n|0\n|0\n|\n|-\n|2020-03-27\n|1026\n|48\n|5\n|11\n|106\n|4\n|0\n|0\n|\n|-\n|2020-03-28\n|1076\n|48\n|5\n|15\n|47\n|0\n|0\n|4\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Bangladesh|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Bangladesh]]\n", "name_user": "Aranya", "label": "safe", "comment": "duplicate word", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Bangladesh"}
{"title_page": "Royal Barry Wills", "text_new": "'''Royal Barry Wills''' (August 21, 1895 \u2013 January 10, 1962) was an American [[architect]] and author. He was a master of the [[Cape Cod (house)|Cape Cod]] type house, particularly its 1930s\u20131950s [[Colonial Revival architecture|Colonial Revival]] incarnation. Houses built to his designs continue to fetch a premium.\n\n==Life and work==\nWills was born in [[Melrose, Massachusetts|Melrose]], [[Massachusetts]], and in 1918 graduated from [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|M.I.T]] as an [[architectural engineer]]. From 1919 until 1925, he worked as a design engineer for the [[Turner Construction Company]] of Boston, while engaging in his own architectural practice on the side. To advance his business, he regularly published sketch plans and elevations in the ''[[Boston Transcript]]''. He also answered questions from readers about architecture. Commissions followed; he became a registered architect in 1925, opening his own Boston office on lower [[Beacon Street]] the same year. With success, his [[architectural firm|firm]] moved to [[Beacon Hill (Boston)|Beacon Hill]]. In 1954, he was elected a [[fellow]] of the [[American Institute of Architects]].<ref>[http://95merriamstreet.com/webcontent/6150/Royal%20Barry%20Wills-Architect.pdf David Gebhard, ''Royal Barry Wills and the American Colonial Revival'']{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe Cape Cod house is ubiquitous in [[New England]] and elsewhere, due in part to its simplicity, which sometimes simply means inexpensive, but also allows for versions that achieve a pure elegance due to their restraint and [[proportion (architecture)|proportion]]s. Will's artistry brought refinement to every level of [[architectural drawing|planning]], [[engineering]] and detail of the Cape Cod model. They were low to the ground, with [[eave]]s just above the windows, and surmounted by an outsized central [[chimney]] (a Wills hallmark). The [[roof pitch]] ranged from {{convert|8|to|10|in}}, vertically, in a {{convert|12|in|adj=on}} run. The [[window sash|sash]] was made up from 24 to 36 individual [[paned window|lights]], and [[clapboard (architecture)|clapboard]]s graduated from a 2{{frac|3|4}}-inch exposure at the [[foundation (engineering)|foundation]], to a typical 4{{frac|1|4}}-inch exposure from the top of the [[window sill]] to the eave. But most of all, Wills emphasized what he termed \"[[scale (spatial)|scale]]\"\u2014the relationship of parts to one another that gives a design perfection and charm. And unlike many architects, he offered \"partial services\", adding to [[general contractor|contractor]] designs without credit.<ref>Royal Barry Wills Associates, ''More Houses for Good Living;'' Architectural Book Publishing Company, New York, New York 1968</ref>\n\nIn 1938, [[Life Magazine]] selected four [[modern architecture|modern architects]] and four traditional architects, asking them to prepare home designs for families in four income categories. In the category for people with $5,000 to $6,000 incomes, the modern design was by [[Frank Lloyd Wright]] and the traditional one by Royal Barry Wills. The family chose the Wills house over the Wright design, and the home was built in [[Edina, Minnesota|Edina]], [[Minnesota]]. With the motto \"no stock plans\", Wills designed buildings not only in New England, but from [[Canada]] to [[Florida]], including Cape Cods, [[garrison (architecture)|garrison]]s, [[saltbox]]es, churches, and, in 1941, a 300-unit housing complex for [[defense (military)|defense]] workers.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Qyf36jw-sNoC&pg=PA28 Jeff Wilkinson, \"Royal Barry Wills\"; ''Old-House Journal'' July-August 1992]</ref>\n\nAuthor of eight books on architecture offering designs and advice, he died in Boston. In 1957, his firm became Royal Barry Wills Associates, and remains active today.\n\n:\"He wanted only to design the indigenous New England house supremely well, and succeeded beyond any other architect.\" <ref>Royal Barry Wills Associates, ''More Houses for Good Living;'' Architectural Book Publishing Company, New York, New York 1968</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110820101151/http://www.royalbarrywills.com/ Royal Barry Wills Associates, architects]\n*[http://www.bobvila.com/sections/home-building/projects/11-modern-colonial/episodes/120-shingles-and-windows/videos/1090010049001-cape-cod-style-architecture-and-royal-barry-wills Bob Vila -- Cape Cod-Style Architecture and Royal Barry Wills]\n*[http://retrorenovation.com/2009/11/02/the-royal-barry-wills-cape-home/ Retro Renovation -- The Royal Barry Wills Cape Cod]\n*[http://retrorenovation.com/2010/07/08/royal-barrys-wills-home-1920-melrose-mass/ Retro Renovation -- The first home that Royal Barry Wills built for his family, Melrose, Mass., 1920]\n*[http://retrorenovation.com/2012/12/12/springfield-housing-project-royal-barry-wills-jan-28-1942/ Retro Renovation -- Images and documentation on the Springfield, Mass. Defense Housing Project designed by Royal Barry Wills.]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110929004707/http://www.royalbarrywills.com/high/large/profile/selected_essays/colonial_revival/cr1.htm Essays on Royal Barry Wills' life and work] by Richard Guy Wilson, Marjorie Henderson Floyd, and The Saturday Evening Post.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wills, Royal Barry}}\n[[Category:Architects from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Colonial Revival Movement]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Institute of Architects]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Melrose, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "'''Royal Barry Wills''' (August 21, 1895 \u2013 January 10, 1962) was an American [[architect]] and author. He was a master of the [[Cape Cod (house)|Cape Cod]] type house, particularly its 1930s\u20131950s [[Colonial Revival architecture|Colonial Revival]] incarnation. Houses built to his designs continue to fetch a premium.\n\n==Life and work==\nWills was born in [[Melrose, Massachusetts|Melrose]], [[Massachusetts]], and in 1918 graduated from [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|M.I.T]] as an [[architectural engineer]]. From 1919 until 1925, he worked as a design engineer for the [[Turner Construction Company]] of Boston, while engaging in his own architectural practice on the side. To advance his business, he regularly published sketch plans and elevations in the ''[[Boston Transcript]]''. He also answered questions from readers about architecture. Commissions followed; he became a registered architect in 1925, opening his own Boston office on lower [[Beacon Street]] the same year. With success, his [[architectural firm|firm]] moved to [[Beacon Hill (Boston)|Beacon Hill]]. In 1954, he was elected a [[fellow]] of the [[American Institute of Architects]].<ref>[http://95merriamstreet.com/webcontent/6150/Royal%20Barry%20Wills-Architect.pdf David Gebhard, ''Royal Barry Wills and the American Colonial Revival'']{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe Cape Cod house is ubiquitous in [[New England]] and elsewhere, due in part to its simplicity, which sometimes simply means inexpensive, but also allows for versions that achieve a pure elegance due to their restraint and [[proportion (architecture)|proportion]]s. Will's artistry brought refinement to every level of [[architectural drawing|planning]], [[engineering]] and detail of the Cape Cod model. They were low to the ground, with [[eave]]s just above the windows, and surmounted by an outsized central [[chimney]] (a Wills hallmark). The [[roof pitch]] ranged from {{convert|8|to|10|in}}, vertically, in a {{convert|12|in|adj=on}} run. The [[window sash|sash]] was made up from 24 to 36 individual [[paned window|lights]], and [[clapboard (architecture)|clapboard]]s graduated from a 2{{frac|3|4}}-inch exposure at the [[foundation (engineering)|foundation]], to a typical 4{{frac|1|4}}-inch exposure from the top of the [[window sill]] to the eave. But most of all, Wills emphasized what he termed \"[[scale (spatial)|scale]]\"\u2014the relationship of parts to one another that gives a design perfection and charm. And unlike many architects, he offered \"partial services\", adding to [[general contractor|contractor]] designs without credit.<ref>Royal Barry Wills Associates, ''More Houses for Good Living;'' Architectural Book Publishing Company, New York, New York 1968</ref>\n\nIn 1938, [[Life Magazine]] selected four [[modern architecture|modern architects]] and four traditional architects, asking them to prepare home designs for families in four income categories. In the category for people with $5,000 to $6,000 incomes, the modern design was by [[Frank Lloyd Wright]] and the traditional one by Royal Barry Wills. The family chose the Wills house over the Wright design, and the home was built in [[Edina, Minnesota|Edina]], [[Minnesota]]. With the motto \"no stock plans\", Wills designed buildings not only in New England, but from [[Canada]] to [[Florida]], including Cape Cods, [[garrison (architecture)|garrison]]s, [[saltbox]]es, churches, and, in 1941, a 300-unit housing complex for [[defense (military)|defense]] workers.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Qyf36jw-sNoC&pg=PA28 Jeff Wikinson, \"Royal Barry Wills\"; ''Old-House Journal'' July-August 1992]</ref>\n\nAuthor of eight books on architecture offering designs and advice, he died in Boston. In 1957, his firm became Royal Barry Wills Associates, and remains active today.\n\n:\"He wanted only to design the indigenous New England house supremely well, and succeeded beyond any other architect.\" <ref>Royal Barry Wills Associates, ''More Houses for Good Living;'' Architectural Book Publishing Company, New York, New York 1968</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110820101151/http://www.royalbarrywills.com/ Royal Barry Wills Associates, architects]\n*[http://www.bobvila.com/sections/home-building/projects/11-modern-colonial/episodes/120-shingles-and-windows/videos/1090010049001-cape-cod-style-architecture-and-royal-barry-wills Bob Vila -- Cape Cod-Style Architecture and Royal Barry Wills]\n*[http://retrorenovation.com/2009/11/02/the-royal-barry-wills-cape-home/ Retro Renovation -- The Royal Barry Wills Cape Cod]\n*[http://retrorenovation.com/2010/07/08/royal-barrys-wills-home-1920-melrose-mass/ Retro Renovation -- The first home that Royal Barry Wills built for his family, Melrose, Mass., 1920]\n*[http://retrorenovation.com/2012/12/12/springfield-housing-project-royal-barry-wills-jan-28-1942/ Retro Renovation -- Images and documentation on the Springfield, Mass. Defense Housing Project designed by Royal Barry Wills.]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110929004707/http://www.royalbarrywills.com/high/large/profile/selected_essays/colonial_revival/cr1.htm Essays on Royal Barry Wills' life and work] by Richard Guy Wilson, Marjorie Henderson Floyd, and The Saturday Evening Post.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wills, Royal Barry}}\n[[Category:Architects from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Colonial Revival Movement]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Institute of Architects]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Melrose, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Barry_Wills"}
{"title_page": "Laura \u0160tefanac", "text_new": "'''Laura \u0160tefanac''' is a [[Croats|Croatian]] paralympic athlete competing in [[javelin throw]], [[hammer throw]], [[discus throw]] and [[shot put]].\n\nShe was born deaf in 1998 in Croatia's capital [[Zagreb]].<ref>[http://www.hrvatskareprezentacija.hr/laura-stefanac-iznad-hendikepa-i-sustava/ hrvatskareprezentacija.hr]</ref>\n\nShe won a gold medal at the Olympic games for deaf people in Samsun (2017.) in [[javelin throw]], as well as 3 gold and 3 silver medals at the European junior championships in [[Trabzon]] 2014<ref>[https://net.hr/ostalo/laura-stefanac-osvojila-zlato-i-dva-srebra/ net.hr]</ref> and [[Karlsruhe]] 2016.\n\nShe is a member of AK Agram from Zagreb.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:\u0160tefanac, Laura}}\n[[Category:Women]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:People from Zagreb]]\n[[Category:Croatian female athletes]]\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Croatia]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "'''Laura \u0160tefanac''' is a [[Croats|Croatian]] paralympic athlete competing in [[javelin throw]], [[hammer throw]], [[discus throw]] and [[shot put]].\n\nShe was born deaf in 1998 in Croatia's capital [[Zagreb]].<ref> [http://www.hrvatskareprezentacija.hr/laura-stefanac-iznad-hendikepa-i-sustava/ hrvatskareprezentacija.hr] </ref>\n\nShe won a gold medal at the Olympic games for deaf people in Samsun (2017.) in [[javelin throw]], as well as 3 gold and 3 silver medals at the European junior championships in [[Trabzon]] 2014<ref> [https://net.hr/ostalo/laura-stefanac-osvojila-zlato-i-dva-srebra/ net.hr] </ref> and [[Karlsruhe]] 2016.\n\nShe is a member of AK Agram from Zagreb.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:\u0160tefanac,Laura}}\n[[Category:Women]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:People from Zagreb]]\n[[Category:Croatian female athletes]]\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Croatia]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laura_%C5%A0tefanac"}
